Definition of UtAssert_Compare_t and the UtAssert_Compare_* enumerator values (UtAssert_Compare_EQ, _NEQ, _LT, _GT, _LTEQ, _GTEQ, _BITMASK_SET, _BITMASK_UNSET)
explanation:
1) UT_COMPARE_TYPE (macro) and any helper macros/constants it uses — The switch dispatch in UtAssert_DoCompare is on UT_COMPARE_TYPE(CompareType, IsUnsigned). To decide which case labels are reachable you must know exactly how this macro maps a CompareType value and the IsUnsigned boolean into the integer/constant used in the switch. The macro (and any constants it references, e.g. offsets/bitmasks) defines the one-to-one mapping between input arguments and case label values; without it you cannot determine whether some case labels are impossible (unreachable).

2) Definition of UtAssert_Compare_t and the UtAssert_Compare_* enumerator values — You need the complete set of legal CompareType inputs and their numeric values so you can enumerate the possible values passed into UT_COMPARE_TYPE. If the enum is sparse, has aliases, or uses explicit numeric assignments this affects which switch outcomes are possible. The enum's definition (all enumerators and values) is required to reason about reachability of each case label.

3) Implementation (source) of UtAssert_GenericIntegerCompare — The static call graph shows this function is the only caller of UtAssert_DoCompare. To assess whether any branch in UtAssert_DoCompare is unreachable in the project you must inspect how the caller constructs and passes CompareType and IsUnsigned (and whether some CompareType values are ever passed, or whether IsUnsigned is fixed). The caller may constrain the arguments so that one or more case labels in DoCompare are never invoked; therefore the caller's implementation is necessary to determine project-level reachability.

(Notes: types such as UtAssert_IntBuf_t/UT_IntCheck_t and standard bool true/false are not needed to decide whether a switch case is reachable; they are only relevant for semantic correctness of comparisons, not for determining if code is unreachable.)
